{
  "_meta": {
    "id": "ingredientCosts",
    "version": "1.0.0",
    "currency": "CAD",
    "unit": "per_100g",
    "provenance": "estimated",
    "createdAt": "2026-07-24",
    "whatThisIs": "A DETERMINISTIC region-agnostic baseline price table used by recipeCost.js to estimate a per-serving ingredient cost. It is NOT live grocery pricing. Live pricing is a future hook (recipeCost.js LIVE_PRICING_HOOK) that is OFF in this build and makes zero network calls.",
    "howEntriesAreShaped": "keywords: { \"<lowercase keyword>\": [pricePer100gCad, \"<grocery category>\"] }. A keyword matches when it appears as a substring of the normalised ingredient name. LONGEST KEYWORD WINS - 'peanut butter' beats 'peanut', 'extra virgin olive oil' beats 'olive oil' beats 'oil'. (The old groceryPrices.js used first-match-wins on a hand-ordered array, which silently priced Peanut Butter as peanuts.)",
    "fallbackRule": "Unknown ingredients are NEVER free. recipeCost.js derives the fallback AT LOAD from this table so it can never drift from the data: (1) if the ingredient's Food row carries one of the 7 grocery categories, use the 75th percentile of the priced entries in that category; (2) otherwise use the 75th percentile of the whole table. WHY P75 AND NOT THE MEAN/MEDIAN: an unmatched ingredient is missing information, and missing information must never be rewarded. Pricing an unknown at or below the middle of the distribution would make a recipe full of unrecognised ingredients rank as the CHEAPEST recipe in the pool and win a cost-ranked sort - the exact failure a $0 default causes, just quieter. P75 is a deliberately conservative upper-middle estimate: it keeps unknown-heavy recipes from winning on price without inflating them to an absurd worst case. Separately, computeRecipeCost() reports `coverage` (share of grams priced by a REAL match, fallbacks excluded) and flags tier 'unknown' below 50% coverage, so a mostly-guessed total is never presented as a measured one.",
    "sanctionedZero": "Water is the ONE entry priced at 0.00. Municipal tap water is ~CAD 0.0000003/100 g, which rounds to 0.00 at this table's precision. That is a MEASURED near-zero, not an unknown defaulting to free - the two are different and the tests assert the difference. GUARD: recipeCost.js matches any 0.00 entry on a WORD BOUNDARY only, never as a bare substring, because 'Watermelon' contains 'water' and a free melon would win every cost-ranked sort.",
    "editing": "Correct a price by editing this file. Nothing is generated. The fallback percentiles recompute automatically from whatever is here.",
    "categories": ["protein", "dairy-eggs", "fruit-veg", "grains", "pantry", "fats-nuts-oils", "drinks"]
  },

